One nice thing these examples also do is make it really simple for detractors to point out what they don&#x27;t like about it. My #1 gripe about go, for example, is this: <a href="https://gobyexample.com/sorting-by-functions" rel="nofollow">https://gobyexample.com/sorting-by-functions</a><p>In a few other languages:<p><pre><code>    // C++
    sort(vs.begin(), vs.end(), 
         [](const string& l, const string& r) -> bool { 
             return l.size() < r.size();
         });

    # Python
    vs.sort(key=lambda s: len(s))
</code></pre>
When they fix this, Go might be the perfect language for me. Until then, I&#x27;m not touching it with a pole.
